# Part II Narrative Principles

## Setting Description
- One characterizing image per new location
- Image must do narrative work (reveal character dynamics, institutional decay, cultural differences)
- No architectural inventories, color catalogs, or exhaustive physical surveys
- Example: Fort Ashmark's half-open gate tells us about institutional decay without describing granite or flagstones

## Reader Interpretation
- Present images without commentary
- Let readers do interpretive work
- When Elara interprets, she's brief and filtered through her diplomat's worldview
- Her interpretations should be slightly wrong — this is her Part II arc

## Elara's Misreading Pattern
- Part II: Elara consistently misreads border situations through Thornfield court lens
- She categorizes, she's certain, she's off
- Reader picks up the pattern before Elara does (dramatic irony)
- She begins recalibrating later in Part II — watch for the turning point

## Senna's Communication Style
- Every letter, dialogue line, indirect message has two layers minimum
- Surface layer: innocent, slightly eccentric, nostalgic
- Hidden layer: operational, connected to Reformist network
- Elara doesn't see hidden layer until reveal
- This applies to ALL Senna communication — no straightforward statements

## Chapter Endings
- Default: irony, not tension
- Reader's knowledge creates tension, not external events or interpersonal standoffs
- Elara's confident certainties are the strongest closing beats
- Avoid contemplative, rest-state endings

## Dialogue Tags
- "Said" and "asked" only
- No creative tags (murmured, whispered, exclaimed, etc.)

## Character Voice Distinctions
- Court diplomats: formal introductions, titles, houses, bows
- Border military: terse, no titles, no protocol
- Example: Drey introduces himself as "Drey" only. Elara gives name, house, delegation.